1
00:00:25,258 --> 00:00:27,175
<i>On the day the world ended...</i>

2
00:00:27,258 --> 00:00:32,592
<i>the fate of mankind was carried
in a small metal box.</i>

3
00:00:42,050 --> 00:00:46,633
<i>In a secret location, architects,
scientists and engineers met...</i>

4
00:00:46,717 --> 00:00:50,175
<i>and concluded that there was
only one hope for our future:</i>

5
00:00:51,800 --> 00:00:54,592
<i>To build an underground city...</i>

6
00:00:54,675 --> 00:00:58,383
<i>designed to keep its citizens
protected for generations to come.</i>

7
00:01:10,217 --> 00:01:12,717
Secure the box.

8
00:01:12,842 --> 00:01:14,717
Set it for 200 years.

9
00:01:14,800 --> 00:01:18,133
We'll keep them in the city for 200 years.

10
00:01:20,341 --> 00:01:21,758
You're certain
that'll be long enough?

11
00:01:21,841 --> 00:01:25,758
None of us can be certain of anything.
We can hope.

12
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:29,800
<i>Growing up with no knowledge
of a world outside...</i>

13
00:01:29,883 --> 00:01:34,550
future generations will be spared sorrow
for what they've lost.

14
00:01:39,716 --> 00:01:44,591
For the good of all mankind.

15
00:01:47,883 --> 00:01:50,800
<i>The box was entrusted to the first mayor...</i>

16
00:01:50,883 --> 00:01:53,133
<i>who was to pass it on
to her successor.</i>

17
00:02:00,758 --> 00:02:02,675
<i>As the years counted down...</i>

18
00:02:02,758 --> 00:02:06,133
<i>the box passed from mayor to mayor.</i>

19
00:02:06,216 --> 00:02:08,383
<i>None knew what secrets it held...</i>

20
00:02:08,466 --> 00:02:11,716
<i>only that it would open
when it was needed most.</i>

21
00:02:14,758 --> 00:02:17,591
<i>But fate ran another course...</i>

22
00:02:18,633 --> 00:02:21,216
<i>and the chain was broken.</i>

23
00:02:30,216 --> 00:02:33,925
<i>The box was tucked away
and forgotten...</i>

24
00:02:34,008 --> 00:02:37,008
<i>and as the city grew
old and began to crumble...</i>

25
00:02:37,091 --> 00:02:41,716
<i>the box quietly clicked open.</i>

26
00:03:29,300 --> 00:03:33,175
- Dad, do you hear that?
- Uh, hurry up. You don't wanna be late.

27
00:03:33,258 --> 00:03:36,216
<i>- I am hurrying.
- I'm proud of you, Son.</i>

28
00:03:36,300 --> 00:03:38,633
- Today's a big day.
- Yeah.

29
00:03:38,716 --> 00:03:42,466
I just hope I don't get assigned
some useless job.

30
00:03:42,550 --> 00:03:45,591
<i>You can't control what job you get on
Assignment Day. That's not the point.</i>

31
00:03:45,675 --> 00:03:49,258
<i>The important thing is to do-</i>

32
00:03:49,341 --> 00:03:51,758
your part.

33
00:03:51,841 --> 00:03:57,466
One, two, three, four...

34
00:03:57,550 --> 00:04:02,550
five, six, seven, eight-

35
00:04:07,341 --> 00:04:09,258
They're getting longer.

36
00:04:09,341 --> 00:04:12,341
<i>- That one was.
- Yeah, and it's the third one this week.</i>

37
00:04:12,425 --> 00:04:14,466
The Generator's
our only source of power.

38
00:04:14,550 --> 00:04:16,550
<i>- All Electricians and Wiremen-
- If it goes-</i>

39
00:04:16,633 --> 00:04:18,675
<i>- are advised to report to their stations.
- we all go.</i>

40
00:04:18,758 --> 00:04:22,466
- That's dramatic.
- Dad, this place is falling apart.

41
00:04:22,550 --> 00:04:26,758
No, I will not just sit around
while Ember collapses.

42
00:04:26,841 --> 00:04:29,591
I'm getting into that Generator,
whatever it takes.

43
00:04:58,883 --> 00:05:01,424
Congratulations...

44
00:05:01,508 --> 00:05:05,341
on achieving
this momentous occasion:

45
00:05:05,424 --> 00:05:08,549
your Assignment Day.

46
00:05:12,341 --> 00:05:14,383
I'm late!

47
00:05:14,466 --> 00:05:16,966
- Lina, are you and your granny all right?
- Yeah, we're fine.

48
00:05:17,049 --> 00:05:19,716
- You all right, Mr. Tock?
- Just another blackout, Lina.

49
00:05:20,966 --> 00:05:22,758
Hi.

50
00:05:31,633 --> 00:05:33,424
<i>Be you eight or 18, the time has come...</i>

51
00:05:33,508 --> 00:05:35,799
<i>- to answer the call to service.
- Hi, Mr. Boaz.</i>

52
00:05:35,883 --> 00:05:38,883
- Stop!
- Produce the Book Of The City Of Ember.

53
00:05:40,841 --> 00:05:44,049
- You need to sign in!
- I'm late!

54
00:05:59,549 --> 00:06:01,466
Psst! Lizzie.

55
00:06:04,299 --> 00:06:08,174
<i>- We swear-
- Eternal loyalty to our city.</i>

56
00:06:08,258 --> 00:06:11,508
We declare our infinite gratitude
to the Builders...

57
00:06:11,591 --> 00:06:13,508
who chose this site
with the greatest care.

58
00:06:13,591 --> 00:06:16,508
We flourish above
our mighty flowing river.

59
00:06:16,591 --> 00:06:20,841
We thrive thanks to the unbounded
capacity of our mighty Generator...

60
00:06:20,924 --> 00:06:23,841
beating at our very center
like a magnificent heart.

61
00:06:23,924 --> 00:06:28,466
Beyond Ember, the darkness
goes on forever in all directions.

62
00:06:28,549 --> 00:06:31,508
Ours is the only light in a dark world.

63
00:06:33,258 --> 00:06:35,216
It's true.

64
00:06:44,174 --> 00:06:46,091
Bag.

65
00:06:58,466 --> 00:07:01,299
Be the first to discover your future.

66
00:07:03,591 --> 00:07:05,716
Reach in, young man.

67
00:07:08,841 --> 00:07:11,841
Read it aloud.

68
00:07:11,924 --> 00:07:14,799
Electrician's Helper.

69
00:07:15,883 --> 00:07:18,008
I get to work in the Generator.

70
00:07:19,966 --> 00:07:22,133
<i>Timekeeper's Assistant.</i>

71
00:07:22,216 --> 00:07:24,133
<i>You get to work with clocks.</i>

72
00:07:27,758 --> 00:07:31,174
<i>- Building Repair Assistant.
- They have a lot of fun.</i>

73
00:07:33,383 --> 00:07:35,716
<i>- Greenhouse Helper.
- That-a girl.</i>

74
00:07:37,174 --> 00:07:40,383
<i>- Potato Peeler.
- You're gonna come in handy.</i>

75
00:07:47,258 --> 00:07:49,883
- Warehouse Clerk.
- A vital job.

76
00:07:56,674 --> 00:07:59,174
Pick one, young lady.

77
00:08:10,758 --> 00:08:12,883
Pipeworks?

78
00:08:12,966 --> 00:08:16,049
Louder, so we can all hear.

79
00:08:17,883 --> 00:08:19,882
I'm a Pipeworks Laborer.

80
00:08:19,966 --> 00:08:23,424
You're a very fortunate girl.
That is an important job.

81
00:08:32,716 --> 00:08:36,716
- Mold Scraper.
- We got a Mold Scraper. Great.

82
00:08:46,632 --> 00:08:50,257
Messenger.

83
00:08:55,674 --> 00:08:58,382
<i>- I picked a dull job, but compared to yours-
- Lina.</i>

84
00:08:58,466 --> 00:09:00,091
<i>- mine's a shining light bulb.
- Lina.</i>

85
00:09:00,174 --> 00:09:02,091
- Scream if you need me.
- Trade with me.

86
00:09:02,132 --> 00:09:04,924
- What?
- Swap jobs. Please. You have to.

87
00:09:05,007 --> 00:09:07,466
You want to work in the Pipeworks?

88
00:09:07,549 --> 00:09:11,216
I want to be Electrician's Helper and work
in the Generator, but Joss won't swap.

89
00:09:11,299 --> 00:09:13,174
I would rather die
than be a Messenger.

90
00:09:13,257 --> 00:09:15,591
I don't want to waste my
time while the whole city crumble-

91
00:09:15,674 --> 00:09:19,341
- Yes. Yes.
- What?

92
00:09:26,174 --> 00:09:28,216
- Thank you, Doon!
- Thanks!

93
00:09:35,632 --> 00:09:38,799
<i>* The light from the lamp is not all *</i>

94
00:09:38,882 --> 00:09:42,799
- * There is a brighter light **
- Mrs. Murdo!

95
00:09:42,882 --> 00:09:45,924
- How was your Assignment Day?
- I'm a Messenger!

96
00:09:46,007 --> 00:09:49,674
That's wonderful, Lina!
Congratulations!

97
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:53,216
Granny!

98
00:09:54,216 --> 00:09:56,591
Granny! Where are you?

99
00:09:57,674 --> 00:10:00,591
I'm a Messenger.

100
00:10:00,632 --> 00:10:04,591
You shouldn't make things up.
You-You're not a Messenger, Lina.

101
00:10:04,674 --> 00:10:06,716
But today was Assignment Day,
remember?

102
00:10:06,799 --> 00:10:09,799
<i>Oh.</i>

103
00:10:09,882 --> 00:10:12,966
- Where's Poppy?
- Poppy?

104
00:10:13,049 --> 00:10:17,632
- Poppy?
- She was helping me look for something.

105
00:10:17,716 --> 00:10:19,882
I- Here's Poppy.

106
00:10:23,549 --> 00:10:25,466
Poppy.

107
00:10:26,466 --> 00:10:28,924
<i>Poppy.</i>

108
00:10:28,966 --> 00:10:32,007
Poppy, take that out of your mouth.

109
00:10:33,466 --> 00:10:36,007
Here.

110
00:10:36,091 --> 00:10:38,549
- It's for you.
- Thank you.

111
00:10:48,049 --> 00:10:51,049
- I made it.
- Yeah, I can tell.

112
00:10:53,132 --> 00:10:57,132
- Uh, what's it for?
- It's for your graduation.

113
00:10:57,216 --> 00:11:00,882
I mean, what does it do?

114
00:11:00,966 --> 00:11:02,924
You'll figure it out.

115
00:11:07,007 --> 00:11:10,757
There's more to a bottle cap than
keeping liquid from leaking out of glass.

116
00:11:10,841 --> 00:11:15,507
The main thing is, pay attention.

117
00:11:15,591 --> 00:11:19,174
Pay close attention to everything-
everything you see.

118
00:11:19,257 --> 00:11:21,966
<i>Notice what no one else notices...</i>

119
00:11:22,049 --> 00:11:25,049
and you'll know
what no one else knows.

120
00:11:25,132 --> 00:11:28,882
<i>What you get is what you get.</i>

121
00:11:30,757 --> 00:11:32,507
What you do with what you get-

122
00:11:32,591 --> 00:11:35,341
<i>That's more the point.</i>

123
00:11:35,424 --> 00:11:38,299
Wouldn't you say?

124
00:11:38,382 --> 00:11:40,716
Really useful, Dad.

125
00:11:43,632 --> 00:11:45,882
Don't you want to eat?

126
00:11:45,966 --> 00:11:48,216
I'm not hungry.

127
00:11:50,215 --> 00:11:53,090
<i>I mean, we'll have to replace those.</i>

128
00:12:07,382 --> 00:12:09,507
Hey.

129
00:12:11,632 --> 00:12:13,507
Shh, shh, shh, shh. Hey, it's okay.

130
00:12:13,590 --> 00:12:15,507
You hurt your wing.

131
00:12:18,424 --> 00:12:20,465
Hmm.

132
00:12:29,632 --> 00:12:32,799
- Good night, Lina.
- Good night, Poppy.

133
00:12:34,257 --> 00:12:37,340
I'll play you the voices
while you fall asleep, okay?

134
00:12:45,215 --> 00:12:48,224
<i>Yoo-hoo.</i>

135
00:12:48,507 --> 00:12:50,465
<i>Yoo-hoo.</i>

136
00:12:52,424 --> 00:12:54,965
Anybody home?

137
00:12:55,049 --> 00:12:57,257
<i>Don't hold dinner for me, darling.</i>

138
00:12:57,340 --> 00:13:00,090
<i>I'll be there before lights out.</i>

139
00:13:00,174 --> 00:13:03,882
<i>Mrs. Mayfleet, your shoes are ready.</i>

140
00:13:03,965 --> 00:13:08,549
Hi, Raine. It's Clary.

141
00:13:08,632 --> 00:13:12,507
The sprinkler system's down
again in number two.

142
00:13:12,590 --> 00:13:16,965
Raine, it's me, Barrow.

143
00:13:17,049 --> 00:13:19,257
I've been thinking about it.

144
00:13:19,340 --> 00:13:21,507
I watch my boy and...

145
00:13:22,590 --> 00:13:25,965
<i>I've come around.
I've changed my mind.</i>

146
00:13:26,049 --> 00:13:28,049
<i>I'm in.</i>

147
00:13:30,632 --> 00:13:32,424
<i>Where do you go?</i>

148
00:14:21,924 --> 00:14:23,840
Lina Mayfleet, reporting for duty!

149
00:14:27,590 --> 00:14:30,132
You're early, Mayfleet.

150
00:14:31,132 --> 00:14:33,132
At ease. At ease.

151
00:14:57,799 --> 00:14:59,757
8:00!

152
00:14:59,840 --> 00:15:02,757
Stations, everybody!

153
00:15:18,882 --> 00:15:21,757
- It's beautiful.
- Wear it proudly.

154
00:15:21,798 --> 00:15:25,548
Take care of it.
Always keep it in good repair.

155
00:15:25,632 --> 00:15:27,632
I will.

156
00:15:29,215 --> 00:15:31,340
Your station is Garn Square.

157
00:15:31,423 --> 00:15:34,090
Stop!

158
00:15:34,173 --> 00:15:37,882
I need to tell you the rules.

159
00:15:37,965 --> 00:15:39,965
One: When a customer-

160
00:15:40,048 --> 00:15:42,423
Gives you a message, repeat it back
to make sure you've got it right.

161
00:15:42,507 --> 00:15:45,423
Two: Always wear the red cape
so people can identify you.

162
00:15:45,465 --> 00:15:48,007
<i>Three: Our customers pay
20 coins for every message...</i>

163
00:15:48,090 --> 00:15:50,882
no matter how far we have
to carry it, so go fast.

164
00:15:50,923 --> 00:15:52,923
I love going fast.

165
00:15:52,965 --> 00:15:55,507
Very good. I'm impressed.

166
00:15:55,590 --> 00:15:57,507
Now go!

167
00:16:02,173 --> 00:16:05,298
Sit. Sit.

168
00:16:05,382 --> 00:16:09,298
These overalls will go
over your clothes.

169
00:16:09,382 --> 00:16:12,340
That belt will have
all the tools you'll need.

170
00:16:12,423 --> 00:16:15,257
And I think there's enough traction
left in these boots.

171
00:16:16,340 --> 00:16:18,965
You need traction to work the pipes.

172
00:16:19,048 --> 00:16:21,215
<i>- Thank you.
- Now, this locker is yours.</i>

173
00:16:21,298 --> 00:16:24,798
You can put in your shoes
and whatnots.

174
00:16:24,882 --> 00:16:27,298
- All right?
- Okay.

175
00:16:27,382 --> 00:16:30,382
All right. Try this.

176
00:16:32,965 --> 00:16:35,715
You've got a big head.

177
00:16:36,757 --> 00:16:38,590
Try this one.

178
00:16:38,673 --> 00:16:40,590
Oh, that fits.

179
00:16:41,673 --> 00:16:44,257
All right, now.
Cut your name in there.

180
00:16:44,340 --> 00:16:46,507
- Why?
- Why?

181
00:16:46,590 --> 00:16:49,215
In case something happens to ya.

182
00:16:49,298 --> 00:16:53,257
The guy who wore this helmet
before you drowned.

183
00:16:53,298 --> 00:16:57,340
If he hadn't cut his name in there,
we wouldn't have known who he was.

184
00:16:58,423 --> 00:17:00,423
Here. Use this.

185
00:17:06,798 --> 00:17:09,757
I think I can figure out what's wrong
with the Generator.

186
00:17:10,798 --> 00:17:13,673
When can I see it? Hmm?

187
00:17:14,757 --> 00:17:18,382
<i>Done.</i>

188
00:17:18,423 --> 00:17:20,757
Sul?

189
00:17:32,757 --> 00:17:35,132
Twenty coins, please.

190
00:17:45,048 --> 00:17:47,298
Hey, slow down.

191
00:17:54,298 --> 00:17:56,090
Clary!

192
00:17:58,007 --> 00:18:00,298
<i>Clary! It's me.</i>

193
00:18:00,382 --> 00:18:02,548
Look at you.

194
00:18:02,632 --> 00:18:04,715
<i>- Roner told me.
- You're my first message.</i>

195
00:18:04,798 --> 00:18:06,923
That's great. I'm ready.

196
00:18:07,007 --> 00:18:08,923
From Arbin Swinn,
the vegetable vendor.

197
00:18:08,965 --> 00:18:11,132
Let me have it.

198
00:18:13,882 --> 00:18:17,673
"If this is a potato,
then I'm 16 and sexy. "

199
00:18:23,048 --> 00:18:24,965
<i>Help!</i>

200
00:18:42,673 --> 00:18:44,590
<i>Stay back.</i>

201
00:18:44,673 --> 00:18:47,173
<i>He could be contaminated.
He's been in the Unknown Region.</i>

202
00:18:47,257 --> 00:18:49,173
<i>Don't go near 'im.</i>

203
00:18:49,256 --> 00:18:53,090
I couldn't see it, but I ran right into it.
I swear. It was as big as a house.

204
00:18:53,173 --> 00:18:56,423
I was just trying to get out
along the river.

205
00:18:56,506 --> 00:18:59,465
<i>It was so dark. I grabbed onto it.</i>

206
00:18:59,548 --> 00:19:02,006
<i>- I had to, before it grabbed me!
- Don't touch him!</i>

207
00:19:02,090 --> 00:19:06,090
Stand back! Back!

208
00:19:06,173 --> 00:19:08,590
I had to! No! Ow!

209
00:19:08,631 --> 00:19:13,465
I knew it was dark,
but I had no idea how dark.

210
00:19:13,548 --> 00:19:16,881
I couldn't see anything.

211
00:19:19,340 --> 00:19:21,590
<i>Why would he risk being thrown in jail-</i>

212
00:19:21,673 --> 00:19:24,923
when everyone knows
it's against the law to go out there?

213
00:19:25,006 --> 00:19:27,513
<i>Come on, move!</i>

214
00:19:27,548 --> 00:19:30,131
There's far too much to do
here to worry about out there.

215
00:19:32,215 --> 00:19:35,631
Your father would have known
how to fix these potatoes.

216
00:19:38,756 --> 00:19:41,090
Don't dig too deep, Lina.

217
00:19:55,006 --> 00:19:58,965
<i>- The whole thing is rusted.
- Yep.</i>

218
00:19:59,048 --> 00:20:01,048
- You know, it ought to be replaced, Sul.
- Yep.

219
00:20:01,131 --> 00:20:05,340
- So where do you store new pipe?
- New pipe?

220
00:20:06,423 --> 00:20:09,131
We haven't had new pipe...

221
00:20:09,215 --> 00:20:11,631
since my second decade here.

222
00:20:11,715 --> 00:20:13,631
Yeah.

223
00:20:13,715 --> 00:20:16,298
We've been patchin' so long,
we have more patches than pipe.

224
00:20:16,381 --> 00:20:18,298
Here, hold that.

225
00:20:18,381 --> 00:20:20,465
Attaboy. That's good.

226
00:20:20,548 --> 00:20:23,756
Round and round we go. There.

227
00:20:23,840 --> 00:20:25,756
All right, we'll check it.

228
00:20:26,881 --> 00:20:29,215
Squeeze it.

229
00:20:32,840 --> 00:20:34,756
Is it holdin'?

230
00:20:34,840 --> 00:20:37,298
Uh, so far.

231
00:20:37,381 --> 00:20:41,840
So far? So far is so good.

232
00:20:41,923 --> 00:20:43,840
Oh.

233
00:20:46,340 --> 00:20:48,381
- W-What's gonna happen?
- Same as always.

234
00:20:48,423 --> 00:20:50,215
- What's that?
- We'll cope.

235
00:20:50,298 --> 00:20:52,090
But what about the blackouts?
They're getting worse.

236
00:20:52,173 --> 00:20:54,090
- They're-They're-They're-
- Slow down, kid.

237
00:20:54,131 --> 00:20:56,756
You have to learn
to take things as they come.

238
00:21:01,881 --> 00:21:05,006
Well, what's th-
What's this tunnel called?

239
00:21:05,090 --> 00:21:08,506
It's Tunnel 25. And this is 26.

240
00:21:08,590 --> 00:21:10,715
How do you know?

241
00:21:15,256 --> 00:21:17,340
Come on.

242
00:21:20,006 --> 00:21:21,923
<i>- What's that for?
- Pressure.</i>

243
00:21:23,006 --> 00:21:25,465
<i>Waterwheel.</i>

244
00:21:25,548 --> 00:21:27,506
And this?

245
00:21:27,590 --> 00:21:30,298
